        <text x="240" y="178" text-anchor="middle" fill="#a78bfa" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.7">Risk</text>
        <line x1="222" y1="152" x2="197" y2="125" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.2"/>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Types of Financial Risk -->
    <h3>Types of financial risk</h3>
    <p><strong>Market risk</strong> comes from price movements: equities, interest rates, currencies, commodities. <strong>Credit risk</strong> is the chance a counterparty defaults. <strong>Operational risk</strong> covers everything else: system failures, fraud, legal liability. Each type requires different measurement and different tools.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Quantifying different risk types with simple models

; Market risk: portfolio loss from a 2-sigma equity move
(define portfolio-value 1000000)
(define daily-vol 0.015)  ; 1.5% daily volatility
(define two-sigma-loss (* portfolio-value (* 2 daily-vol)))
(display "2-sigma daily market loss: $")
(display (round two-sigma-loss)) (newline)

; Credit risk: expected loss = PD × LGD × EAD
(define prob-default 0.02)       ; 2% probability of default
(define loss-given-default 0.60) ; recover 40%, lose 60%
(define exposure 500000)
(define expected-credit-loss (* prob-default loss-given-default exposure))
(display "Expected credit loss: $")
(display (round expected-credit-loss)) (newline)

; Operational risk: frequency × severity
(define events-per-year 3)
(define avg-loss-per-event 25000)
(define expected-op-loss (* events-per-year avg-loss-per-event))
(display "Expected operational loss: $")
(display expected-op-loss) (newline)

(display "Total expected annual loss: $")
(display (round (+ (* two-sigma-loss 252) expected-credit-loss expected-op-loss)))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Quantifying risk types

# Market risk: 2-sigma daily loss
portfolio = 1_000_000
daily_vol = 0.015
two_sigma_loss = portfolio * 2 * daily_vol
print(f"2-sigma daily market loss: \${two_sigma_loss:,.0f}")

# Credit risk: EL = PD × LGD × EAD
pd, lgd, ead = 0.02, 0.60, 500_000
ecl = pd * lgd * ead
print(f"Expected credit loss: \${ecl:,.0f}")

# Operational risk
op_loss = 3 * 25_000
print(f"Expected operational loss: \${op_loss:,.0f}")

print(f"Total expected annual loss: \${two_sigma_loss * 252 + ecl + op_loss:,.0f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Hedging Strategies -->
    <h3>Hedging strategies</h3>
    <p>A <strong>hedge</strong> takes an offsetting position to reduce exposure. A wheat farmer sells futures to lock in today's price. An airline buys fuel futures to lock in costs. A perfect hedge eliminates risk but also eliminates upside. Most hedges are partial: reduce variance without zeroing it out.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Hedging with futures: lock in a price

(define (hedged-outcome spot-price futures-price quantity)
  ; Farmer sells futures at futures-price
  ; At delivery: sells at spot, settles futures difference
  (let ((spot-revenue (* spot-price quantity))
        (futures-gain (* (- futures-price spot-price) quantity)))
    (+ spot-revenue futures-gain)))

(define futures-price 5.00)  ; locked in at $5/bushel
(define quantity 10000)      ; 10,000 bushels

(display "Futures lock-in price: $") (display futures-price) (newline)
(display "---") (newline)

; Scenario 1: price drops to $4
(display "Spot = $4.00: revenue = $")
(display (hedged-outcome 4.00 futures-price quantity)) (newline)

; Scenario 2: price stays at $5
(display "Spot = $5.00: revenue = $")
(display (hedged-outcome 5.00 futures-price quantity)) (newline)

; Scenario 3: price rises to $6 — farmer misses upside
(display "Spot = $6.00: revenue = $")
(display (hedged-outcome 6.00 futures-price quantity)) (newline)

; All outcomes = $50,000 regardless of spot price
(display "Perfect hedge: all outcomes equal $")
(display (* futures-price quantity))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Hedging with futures

def hedged_outcome(spot, futures_price, quantity):
    spot_revenue = spot * quantity
    futures_gain = (futures_price - spot) * quantity
    return spot_revenue + futures_gain

futures_price = 5.00
quantity = 10_000

for spot in [4.00, 5.00, 6.00]:
    rev = hedged_outcome(spot, futures_price, quantity)
    print(f"Spot = \${spot:.2f}: revenue = \${rev:,.0f}")

print(f"Perfect hedge: all outcomes = \${futures_price * quantity:,.0f}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 3. Value at Risk -->
    <h3>Value at Risk (VaR)</h3>
    <p><strong>Value at Risk</strong> answers one question: what is the maximum loss over a given period at a given confidence level? A 1-day 95% VaR of $50,000 means there is a 5% chance of losing more than $50,000 in one day. VaR is easy to communicate but dangerous to trust: it says nothing about how bad losses get beyond the threshold. A detailed treatment of VaR models belongs in Finance II.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Parametric VaR (variance-covariance method)
; Assumes returns are normally distributed

; VaR = portfolio_value × z_score × volatility × sqrt(time)

(define (var-parametric value vol confidence-z days)
  (* value confidence-z vol (sqrt days)))

(define portfolio 1000000)
(define annual-vol 0.20)
(define daily-vol (/ annual-vol (sqrt 252)))

; 1-day 95% VaR (z = 1.645)
(display "1-day 95% VaR: $")
(display (round (var-parametric portfolio daily-vol 1.645 1))) (newline)

; 1-day 99% VaR (z = 2.326)
(display "1-day 99% VaR: $")
(display (round (var-parametric portfolio daily-vol 2.326 1))) (newline)

; 10-day 95% VaR (used by regulators)
(display "10-day 95% VaR: $")
(display (round (var-parametric portfolio daily-vol 1.645 10))) (newline)

; VaR limitation: says nothing about tail losses
(display "VaR caveat: 5% of the time, losses EXCEED this number")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

# Parametric VaR

def var_parametric(value, vol, z, days):
    return value * z * vol * math.sqrt(days)

portfolio = 1_000_000
annual_vol = 0.20
daily_vol = annual_vol / math.sqrt(252)

print(f"1-day 95% VaR: \${var_parametric(portfolio, daily_vol, 1.645, 1):,.0f}")
print(f"1-day 99% VaR: \${var_parametric(portfolio, daily_vol, 2.326, 1):,.0f}")
print(f"10-day 95% VaR: \${var_parametric(portfolio, daily_vol, 1.645, 10):,.0f}")
print("VaR caveat: 5% of the time, losses EXCEED this number")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 4. Insurance and Diversification -->
    <h3>Insurance and diversification as risk tools</h3>
    <p><strong>Diversification</strong> is free risk reduction: holding uncorrelated assets shrinks portfolio variance without sacrificing expected return. <strong>Insurance</strong> transfers catastrophic risk to someone who can pool it across many policyholders. Both reduce the impact of any single bad outcome, but through different mechanisms &mdash; diversification averages across assets, insurance averages across people.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Diversification: portfolio volatility drops with more assets

(define (portfolio-vol single-vol n correlation)
  ; For n equal-weight assets with uniform pairwise correlation
  ; sigma_p = sigma * sqrt((1/n) + ((n-1)/n) * rho)
  (* single-vol
     (sqrt (+ (/ 1 n)
              (* (/ (- n 1) n) correlation)))))

(define stock-vol 0.30)  ; 30% annual vol per stock

(display "Portfolio volatility (rho=0.3):") (newline)
(display "  1 stock:   ") (display (round (* 100 (portfolio-vol stock-vol 1 0.3)))) (display "%") (newline)
(display "  5 stocks:  ") (display (round (* 100 (portfolio-vol stock-vol 5 0.3)))) (display "%") (newline)
(display "  10 stocks: ") (display (round (* 100 (portfolio-vol stock-vol 10 0.3)))) (display "%") (newline)
(display "  30 stocks: ") (display (round (* 100 (portfolio-vol stock-vol 30 0.3)))) (display "%") (newline)
(display "  100 stocks:") (display (round (* 100 (portfolio-vol stock-vol 100 0.3)))) (display "%") (newline)

; Floor: even with infinite assets, vol → sigma * sqrt(rho)
(display "Undiversifiable floor: ")
(display (round (* 100 (* stock-vol (sqrt 0.3))))) (display "%")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

# Diversification benefit

def portfolio_vol(stock_vol, n, rho):
    return stock_vol * math.sqrt(1/n + (n-1)/n * rho)

vol = 0.30
rho = 0.3

print("Portfolio volatility (rho=0.3):")
for n in [1, 5, 10, 30, 100]:
    pv = portfolio_vol(vol, n, rho)
    print(f"  {n:>3} stocks: {pv:.0%}")

floor = vol * math.sqrt(rho)
print(f"Undiversifiable floor: {floor:.0%}")
`} />
    </div>


